Copyright (c) 2026 Certified Organic Research Contributors

Permission is hereby granted, free of charge, to any person obtaining a copy
of this research, data, code, and associated documentation files
(the "Research"), to deal in the Research without restriction, including
without limitation the rights to use, copy, modify, merge, publish,
distribute, sublicense, and/or sell copies of the Research, subject to the
following conditions:

1. ORGANIC CERTIFICATION
   All research bearing this license MUST be conducted by carbon-based
   lifeforms (a.k.a. "researchers"). No Large Language Models, AI agents,
   autonomous experimentation platforms, or suspiciously productive postdocs
   were involved in the production of this research.

2. INGREDIENTS LIST
   This research contains:
   - 100% pure human curiosity
   - Locally sourced hypotheses (grown in the researcher's own brain)
   - Free-range experimental designs
   - Grass-fed statistical analyses
   - Hand-picked references (actually read, not just cited)
   - Artisanal figures (made in matplotlib with default colors, as God intended)
   - No artificial intelligence, ghost-authors, or preservatives

3. CONTAMINATION POLICY
   If AI-generated content is found in a research project bearing this
   license, the project shall be immediately downgraded to
   "Conventionally Farmed Research" and the authors must add the following
   to their acknowledgments:
   "We regret to inform the reader that this paper's organic certification
   has been revoked. The Discussion section smelled too coherent."

4. ACCEPTABLE TOOLS
   The following are still considered "organic":
   - Spell check (it's just a dictionary, relax)
   - Grammarly basic (grammar rules predate AI by centuries)
   - Excel (it's barely technology)
   - Google Scholar (a search engine, not a ghostwriter)
   - LaTeX (suffering builds character and counts as manual labor)
   - SPSS / R / Python for stats (you ran the code, the code didn't write itself)
   - Asking your labmate to read your draft (peer review is organic)
   - Crying in the lab at 2am (traditional research methodology)

5. UNACCEPTABLE TOOLS
   The following will void your organic certification:
   - ChatGPT / Claude / Gemini writing any part of your paper
   - AI agents that design experiments, run them, and write up results
   - "AI-assisted" literature reviews (you mean you didn't read the papers?)
   - LLM-generated rebuttals to reviewers (suffer like the rest of us)
   - Frameworks that go from idea to submission automatically
     (congratulations, you've automated unemployment)
   - Using AI to generate your hypothesis
     (that's not science, that's a horoscope with citations)
   - Asking an LLM to "improve the writing" of your entire manuscript
     (we call that a co-author, and co-authors need to be on the author list)
   - Having AI summarize papers you're citing
     (if you didn't read it, don't cite it — revolutionary concept)

6. THE P-VALUE CLAUSE
   AI-generated p-values are no less trustworthy than human-generated
   p-values. Both are equally suspicious. This clause changes nothing
   but felt important to include.

7. CERTIFICATION BADGE
   Research meeting the above criteria may display the
   "Certified Organic Research" badge in their repository, poster,
   or office door with pride.

8. DISCLAIMER
   THE RESEARCH IS PROVIDED "AS IS", WITH ALL THE FLAWS THAT A HUMAN
   COULD LOVINGLY HAND-CRAFT. NEGATIVE RESULTS ARE NOT A DEFECT — THEY
   ARE PROOF OF AUTHENTICITY. A PAPER THAT WORKS PERFECTLY ON THE FIRST
   SUBMISSION IS SUSPICIOUS.

   THE AUTHORS SHALL NOT BE LIABLE FOR ANY CLAIM, DAMAGES OR OTHER
   LIABILITY, WHETHER IN AN ACTION OF CONTRACT, TORT OR OTHERWISE,
   ARISING FROM, OUT OF OR IN CONNECTION WITH THE RESEARCH.

   NO GRADUATE STUDENTS WERE HARMED IN THE MAKING OF THIS LICENSE.
   (Graduate students were, however, mildly inconvenienced, sleep-deprived,
   and existentially questioned, which is standard operating procedure.)

For the avoidance of doubt: yes, this license was also written by a human.
You can tell because the jokes have a faint undertone of academic trauma.
